STAT 306 Project - Exporing variables that affect housing price¶

by Group D3 - Tianne Lee, Lisanne Huijs, Kai Duan, Jeff Huang

Introduction¶

Housing prices is a widely discussed topic, present and past. Moreover, the topic of housing prices is relevant to everyone.

This project aims to investigate the relationship between the median house price among other variables. We would like to see which factors contribute to housing prices the most. Such study will help us understand and be more familiar with the housing market, helping us prepare for future investments.

Data source¶

The dataset is a modified version of the California Housing dataset based on the 1990 US census data, from the textbook Hands-On Machine Learning notebooks by Aurélien Géron. The CSV file of the data is linked here.

This dataset is about houses found in given California block groups (districts) based on the 1990 census data. Each observation in the dataset corresponds to a district.

The variables in this dataset are:

  • longitude: longitude of the district (Continuous, unit = degree)
  • latitude: latitude of the district (Continuous, unit = degree)
  • housing_median_age: median housing age of the district (Continuous, unit = years)
  • total_rooms: total rooms in the district (Continuous, unit = count)
  • total_bedrooms: total bedrooms in the district (Continuous, unit = count)
  • population: total population in the district (Continuous, unit = count)
  • households`: total households in the district (Continuous, unit = count)
  • median_income: median income of people in the district (Continuous, unit = dollars)
  • ocean_proximity: distance to the ocean, with categories [<1H OCEAN, INLAND, NEAR OCEAN, NEAR BAY, ISLAND] (Categorical, no unit)
  • median_house_value: response variable, median house value in the district (Continuou, unit = dollars)

Data preprocessing¶

The variable median_house_value is our response variable. In order to explore the relationships more clearly, we would do some data cleaning prior carrying out linear modelling.

We observe that the dataset uses a lot of "total" counts in a district, for example, total_rooms and total_bedrooms. We think it would be reasonable to convert the total count to mean values by dividing the values with the number of households in the district.

In [3]:
house <- house %>% mutate(rooms_per_household = total_rooms/households,
                       bedrooms_per_household = total_bedrooms/households,
                       population_per_household = population/households)

The full model¶

In the introduction part, we created a full model (full_model) that contained every explanatory variable. The model is as follows: $$Y = -2355682 - 27663.39 x_1 -26352.91 x_2 + 1073.46 x_3 - 3.59 x_4 + 59.47 x_5 -38.88 x_6 \

  • 82.75 x_7 + 40338.97 x_8 - 37399.14 x_{91} +148227.83 x_{92} - 4045.56 x_{93} + 3976.53 x_{94}\

+-3326.76 x_{10} + 25673.12 x_{11} + 64.50 x_{12} $$

where

  • $x_1$ = longitude
  • $x_2$ = latitude
  • $x_3$ = housing_median_age
  • $x_4$ = total_rooms
  • $x_5$ = total_bedrooms
  • $x_6$ = population
  • $x_7$ = households
  • $x_8$ = median_income
  • $x_{91}$ = ocen_proximityINLAND
  • $x_{92}$ = ocen_proximityISLAND
  • $x_{93}$ = ocen_proximityNEAR BAY
  • $x_{94}$ = ocen_proximityNEAR OCEAN
  • $x_{10}$ = rooms_per_household
  • $x_{11}$ = bedrooms_per_household
  • $x_{12}$ = population_per_household

After preprocessing, we dropped a few variables and arrived at a second full model (full_2) that contains every remaining variable that we didn't drop. The model is as follows: $$Y = 39064.14 + 978.73 x_1 + 0.60 x_2 + 38382.88 x_3 - 72469.19 x_{41} + 180019.08 x_{42} + 12828.94 x_{43} + 17183.97 x_{44} + 9831.25 x_5 -352.84 x_6$$

where

  • $x_1$ = housing_median_age
  • $x_2$ = population
  • $x_3$ = median_income
  • $x_{41}$ = ocen_proximityINLAND
  • $x_{42}$ = ocen_proximityISLAND
  • $x_{43}$ = ocen_proximityNEAR BAY
  • $x_{44}$ = ocen_proximityNEAR OCEAN
  • $x_{5}$ = bedrooms_per_household
  • $x_{6}$ = population_per_household

Variable selection¶

In order to build an unbiased model from the variables in full_2, we split the data into 2 equally sized sections. One section will be used to select the variables, and the other section will be used to fit the model.

In [9]:
set.seed(1234)
dt <- sample.int(nrow(house), nrow(house) / 2)
section1 <- house[dt,]
section2 <- house[-dt,]

We will use forward selection in section1 to choose the variables to use in our model. The below code shows the variables selected by the algorithm for each number of variables to include in the model.

the variables we will choose to include in our final model will be:

  • population
  • median_income
  • ocean_proximity (includes 4 dummy variables)
  • bedrooms_per_household
  • population_per_household

Fitting the inference model¶

We will then fit the our inference using the second part of the data (section2) and the variables selected above.

In [12]:
fit_final <- lm(median_house_value ~ 
housing_median_age
+ population
+ median_income
+ bedrooms_per_household
+ ocean_proximity
+ population_per_household, data = section2)
In [13]:
ggplot(fit_final, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0)

qqplot_resid <- qqnorm(resid(fit_final)) 
qqline(resid(fit_final)) 

plot(section2$median_income, section2$median_house_value, main ="Reference plot", xlab = "Median income", ylab = "Median house value")

There is an obvious diagonal line in our residual plot because that is upper limit of our response variable. There are no data points with a medin_house_value beyond 500000 (shown above in the reference scatter plot). However, we can see our residual plot has heteroscedasticity. The qqplot also does not suggest that our residuals are normally distributed. As a result, we will fit another model using log(y) as the response variable.

Final Inference Model with log(Y)¶

In [14]:
fit_final_log <- lm(log(median_house_value) ~ 
housing_median_age
+ population
+ median_income
+ bedrooms_per_household
+ ocean_proximity
+ population_per_household, data = section2)

tidy(fit_final_log) %>% mutate_if(is.numeric, round, digits = 3)

Our final model is: $$log(Y) = 11.427 + 0.002 x_1 + x_1 + 0.173 x_2 +0.062 x_3 -0.511 x_{41} + 0.691 x_{42} + 0.023 x_{43} + 0.033 x_{44} -0.001 x_5$$

  • $x_{41}$ = ocen_proximityINLAND
  • $x_{42}$ = ocen_proximityISLAND
  • $x_{43}$ = ocen_proximityNEAR BAY
  • $x_{44}$ = ocen_proximityNEAR OCEAN
  • $x_{5}$ = population_per_household

From the residial and qqplot above, we can now see that our residuals are quite normally distributed and have constant variance. Hence, we will choose this log model as our final model.

Model performance¶

In [16]:
summary(fit_final_log)$r.squared
0.616874419274384

Because the goal of our project is to draw inference not prediction, we will not be conducting any predictions on new data. With an $R^2$ value of around 0.62, around 62% of the variance for median_house_value is explained by our model. Our group thinks that this number is acceptable because there might be a lot of other factors that affect the housing market and the relationships might not be captured by a linear model.

For a linear model, we are satisfied with the result we got.

Conclusion¶

According to our analysis, we found the best fit model to be $$log(Y) = 11.427 + 0.002 x_1 + x_1 + 0.173 x_2 +0.062 x_3 -0.511 x_{41} + 0.691 x_{42} + 0.023 x_{43} + 0.033 x_{44} -0.001 x_5$$ , where Y and each of the x_i variables are stated above.

This means that other than ocean_proximity == inland and population_per_household, all other variables holds a positive relationship to log(Y), which essentially means a positive relationship to Y.

Through this analysis, we learnt that locations are specifically important when determining the median house value. Variables like longitude and latitude do not affect the housing price, and to our surprise, the age of the house do not matter as much too. We speculate this is because the land that the house is built on has a lot more value than the building architecture itself.

This project helped us gain a deeper understanding of the housing market, and we think that the process of doing this project pushed us towards a brighter direction towards our future.
